text.tspan: Motivation
Insider threats are on the rise, current commer-
cial software can monitor, log, and prevent
access to designated files and directories it
remains difficult to predict and prevent un-
authorized insider usage. Due to the gaps in
research in the area, the focus of this study
is to more accurately predict insider threats.
Results
After completion of the prediction it has been shown that the model is off
by about 20% when predicting malicious or mistake commands.
The results of the high-fidelity simulation show that not only is the softw-
are I wrote ineffective as a terminal but that it is also easy to bypass.
the participants were able to escape it and after that became untrace-
able to my system.
Overall the process has not proved anything of stastical signifigance.
At least I tried.
Why the linux terminal?
Linux has been chosen because of the
ubiquity of the operating systems based on
it are connected to the internet in servers
around the gloobe. It is also transferable to all
POSIX-compatable terminal environments that
are in use today.
Data Sources
There are three main sources of data used for the machi-
ne learning model. The first is an un-edited history file from
my personal laptop, running Ubuntu 16.10. Second is a list
of malicious and mistake commands assembled from my res-
earch. Finally is the UNIX User Dataset from Purdue University.
It is 9 sets of cleaned data gathered over a period of two years.
Due to the nature of of the two gathered datasets I wrote simple prog-
rams in the Python language to remove any unnessecary items from both
files. It also saved them in a CSV (comma seperated values) format for easy
upload to Amazon's S3 storage service. They were then used by the machine
learning software to generate the model. The CSV files consisted of a com-
mand and a label stating which catageory (normal, malicious, and mistake)
the given command likely was. Due to the lack of open data for the latter two
the vast majority of data points falls into the normal catagory.

Conclusions
Methods
A Practical Application of Machine
Learning-Based Classification Techniques
to Proactively Identify Insider Threats
Refrences, Source Code, Material
The method adapted is to utilize the Amazon Machine Learning software, it
will be trained on a dataset comprised of normal user situations, crafted
mistakes, and malicious activity. After providing the training dataset, the
software will be instructed to make predictions against similar datasets to
verify accuracy. It will then be tested against a human actor that will sim-
ulate multiple different roles, and test predictions in a high-fidelity simulation.
A testing dataset of 100 commands will be given to the model for batch
prediction and will be evaluated for statistical accuracy. In the high-
fidelity test, the students in Embry RIddle Arenoutical University's
Hacking Club were given a normal username and password to
log in with an attempt to gain root access like an insider would
do when looking for confidential information. The commands
used by the students were evaluated in real-time by the
model, allowed or not, and then logged. These results will
be examined further to determine problem areas.
Based on the results of the tests it has
been determined that while the model
isn't that unaccurae when given spec-
ial weighting. This is likely due to the
lack of data in the malicious and mis-
take catagories. I think it would be
prudent to ask organizations to pu-
blish the cleaned logs after an att-
ack so that further research can be
performed on the commands found
in the 'wild'. Another problem ide-
ntified during this study is the pro-
gramming needed to accurately
capture information from a live
terminal environment. While I
was able to create a fake prompt
it was severly limited and that
skews the data from the simula-
tion. Future research will be nee-
ded in order to determine how to
best approach the problem of pr-
actical proactive intruder detect-
ion. I theorize that larger data-
sets comprising of more points
such as timestamps and keyboard
information would help better
track user behavior in an attempt
to establish recognizable patterns
by neural networks.
While not a success in a traditional
sense, this study was successful in
identifying areas for future research
and has shown that it is practical to
evaluate commands on-the-fly in a se-
rver environment. The value of incre-
ased security far outweighs the small
lag experianced by the end user that is
little more than when on a slow network.
